# Rust Core Standards

- Use explicit types on all public function signatures and complex bindings.
- Wrap primitive IDs in newtypes: `struct UserId(String);` — never pass raw `String` for IDs.
- Error handling: `thiserror` in library crates, `anyhow` in binaries. No raw string errors.
- Never use `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in production code; propagate with `?`.
- Default collections: `Vec` for sequences, `HashMap` for maps; pre-allocate when size is known.
- Use Builder pattern only for structs with complex initialization; use plain constructors otherwise.
- Document every public item (enforced by workspace lints in library crates).

```rust
// BAD
fn get_user(id: String) -> User { users.get(&id).unwrap().clone() }

// GOOD
fn get_user(id: &UserId) -> Result<User, DomainError> {
    self.storage.find_user(id)
}
```
